went through Johns Hopkins individual states data (this seems to be what covidexitstrategy uses but more up to date) and ballparked the % chance that each state would be over 10% positivity rate. I took a sum of these to get my estimate and adjusted all estimates by plus/minus 20% to get a feel for a confidence interval. Mean estimate was 14.09 and my bounds were 11.28, 15.29.

The first obvious thing to observe is that we are forecasting/looking forward a very short period of time. Today's observed value of number of states w/ positivity >=10% (denote NUM_STATES) is a very strong forecast for tomorrow's NUM_STATES (there is a limited amount of variance left to be realized over the course of the next day). Therefore, it seemed unintuitive to try to fit a sophisticated logarithmic model or time series regression looking back historically over a significant period of time for a couple of reasons. 1.) The variance in our model prediction may far exceed the amount of variance remaining before the settlement date 2.) The most recent "moves" in the Covid positivity rate by day are intuitively a better prediction of tomorrow's move (historical moves looking back across a longer time may not be a good reference point for this). Thus, I will be looking at moves over the course of the last 10 days, and discount moves prior to that as a poor sample for our population parameter (today's move). Important to note: there is a trade-off here between sample size and representativeness of our sample. Last week's moves may better predict tomorrow's move better than last month's moves, but you will be drawing from a smaller sample and thus have greater variance.

Methodology: To construct our predictions for this question, first, we defined a benchmark based on historical values. Subsequently, tried to both support and contradict our initial hypothesis with quantitative as well as qualitative metrics. Finally, we looked at edge cases to fine-tune our prediction values between the buckets.

Summary of the problem: The objective is to assess the number of US states that will report a COVID-19 positivity rate greater than 10.0%. Positivity rate is the positive cases that have been surfaced from testing: [Positive Cases / Total Tests], rolled on the past 7 days [1]. This data is updated daily and comes from the COVID Tracking Project.

Looking at positiveIncrease and totalTestResultIncrease over the past 7 days we can gain an idea of what to expect in terms of positivity rate. In addition to this, if we note that the eventual metric will be calculated using a 7-day rolling average, we can be quite certain our range will fall between 11 and 15, especially considering the current range is around 13~14.

Summary: take the latest rolling 7-day average, predict whether states with borderline positivity rate will be above 10% based on the assumption that the rolling positivity rate is a random walk with a linear trend.

Currently there are 12 states with a positivity rate > 10% and one (Arkansas) that is at 10.0% flat. The most likely path to 6-10 states appears to be Arkansas, Kansas, and Florida all falling below 10%. Arkansas appears to be a coin flip right now. I would put the probability of Kansas falling below 10.0% at <10% given that its weekly rolling average has remained between approximately 11 and 12.5% for the past two weeks. And similarly, Florida I think also has a sub-10% probability of dipping below 10 given that its positivity rate has been decreasing more or less linearly for the past two weeks at a rate of 0.24 percentage points per day, so it is not on track to go below the 10 mark for another 10.5 days. If we assume these three events are independent we can see that the probability of all three states falling out of the money in the next 2 days is less than 0.5*0.1*0.1 = 0.005.

I looked at the percent changes in positivity over the past 13 data points and for each state, generated a random sample of 100,000 percent changes from this original data. I used decaying probability weights so that the most recent data was represented more in the sample than older data. Finally I summed over the state samples to obtain a sample of the number of states with a rate greater than 10%. All of this work led to the obvious conclusion that the number in two days is extremely likely to be between 11 and 15 states. I did increase the chances for 6-10 and 16-20 states by 1% each to account for a bit more uncertainty.

The opening of schools and universities will create a new spike in cases, despite efforts to maintain distance and contact trace. Those who may have previously been isolated may now be exposed if even one person from a family is going to a school and coming into contact with hundreds of others. Additionally, the CDC release that limits testing to only those with symptoms should increase the COVID+ rate as those with symptoms are more likely to test positive. By September 1, those who contracted the disease as schools first opened should have had enough time to develop symptoms, get tested, and have the results come back. This should keep the rates steady. With 12 states currently above 10%, I think it's possible that a few more reach the threshold. A four state increase seems possible, but unlikely.
Rates may jump or decrease in the south based on the hurricanes. Either way, I feel they will stay within the 11-15 window with a higher potentiality to drop.

After using the current positivity rates for each state gotten from https://www.covidexitstrategy.org, I ran a Monte Carlo simulation. In each trial, I assumed each state's rate would change by some normally distributed amount, where that error has mean 0 and standard deviation .5%. I also added the same "national error" to every state according to a normal distribution with mean 0 and standard deviation .3%. I got these numbers by looking at a few states' and US' trends over time, and failing to think of any national event that would happen by then that might imply a directional move.

As of 7/9 there are 10 US States with positivity rates greater than 10% with rates ranging from 10.38%-26.81%. There are 5 states with ranges from 8%-10%. Of those 5, 3 have 7 day declining averages or flat(ish). Of the 10 states identified earlier, the ones closest to 10% (10-12%) have increasing 7-day avg numbers. The United States as a whole has been increasing daily since an early low of 4.4% in early June. The trend is negative and therefore unlikely that the current number of 10 can be reduced in the face of growing cases, however, some states are having success which may push neighbors to follow suit so I assigned a meaningful probability to a slight decline (6-10). The states that breach 10% by September 1, 2020 could possibly replace states that exit that bucket, which given the general desire and efforts to help control the oubreak (albeit on a limited basis) I assigned a greater than 50% likelihood. Given the negative case trends, a worsening is certainly possible and I needed to assign a meaningful probability. Anything less than 15% I think would under-represent the chance of occurrence. Lastly, given the state of the pandemic, we have to acknowledge that things could spiral out of control which is why I assigned a 5% chance to 21 or more. I assigned a zero to 5 or fewer because that would require a near extinguishment of the virus from global hotspots. There is nothing that indicates to me that this is possible.

Currently 10 above 10% and all increasing or flat rates. 3 are on track to go above 10% soon. Nine others would cross the 10% threshold in the timeframe on current trajectories and two are possible, but uncertain. That gives 21 as the base rate on current trends. Test numbers are increasing in almost all states; constraints in the availability of tests seem likely to bite soon. Without adequate testing renewed lockdowns (at least partial) will be required to stay ahead of the spread. In any case, the general pattern appears to be that when test availability is constrained, they are prioritised towards higher risk populations. That would tend to support the general trend towards rising Covid positivity rates as those tested are more likely to have the disease. However over a two month period, strict lockdowns could flatten the curve as happened in the Northeast from March (although that really took at least a month to become evident). Overall, it is likely some of the states now on a trajectory towards >10% will be able to flatten the curve, but others may actually pick up speed that are not there yet. The partisan nature of acceptance of public health measures will be a significant factor in which states take which route.
